description: Measure voltage across both the switched cable indicator LED and its series resistor (if present) to determine whether they are dropping excess voltage, or are open/faulty and causing the voltage drop seen at the relay output., outcome='The PSU Status LED (green) has 1.2916 V across its anode to cathode, indicating it is not open. The series resistor for the PSU Green LED has a voltage drop of 10.696 V (from 11.9876 V at one end to 1.2916 V at the other), indicating it is dropping a substantial portion of the supply voltage.\nCurrent persistent circuit state [differences with the starting state]:\nNo circuit-level changes introduced by diagnostics.', precise_action_cost=50.0, cost_breakdown=[('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('invert_enclosure', 10.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0)], simplified_outcome=None), DiagnosticActionResult(action=
name: Test -> switched cable indicator LED and series resistor (control module),
description: Test the voltage across the switched cable indicator LED and its series resistor (not the PSU Status LED) to determine if this indicator path is dropping a significant voltage or is open, which would explain the low output voltage to the load., outcome='Diagnostic summary:\nThe voltage across the Ambient Light Sensor is approximately 0.119\u202fV, and across the Sensor Bias Resistor is approximately 11.87\u202fV. The indicator path is not open and is dropping a significant voltage.\nCurrent persistent circuit state [differences with the starting state]:\nNo circuit-level changes introduced by diagnostics.', precise_action_cost=45.0, cost_breakdown=[('open_inspection_panel', 5.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0)], simplified_outcome=None), DiagnosticActionResult(action=
name: Test -> switched cable physical connection (control module to load module),
description: Test the continuity and orientation (wiring) of the physical connections between the switched-cable output of the control module and the input of the load module. A miswiring or accidental cross-connection could divert current through unintended paths, explaining the voltage drop and lamp cycling., outcome='Continuity tests confirm short, low-resistance paths from Control Output Cable (+) to Load Input Cable (+) and from Control Output Cable (−) to Load Input Cable (−). Physical inspections show that positive and negative cables are connected to their corresponding terminals without polarity inversion. No polarity inversion is detected in the current wiring between the control and load modules.\nCurrent persistent circuit state [differences with the starting state]:\nNo circuit-level changes introduced by diagnostics.', precise_action_cost=110.0, cost_breakdown=[('test_path_continuity', 30.0), ('test_path_continuity', 30.0), ('open_inspection_panel', 5.0), ('inspect_connections', 10.0), ('inspect_connections', 10.0), ('open_inspection_panel', 5.0), ('inspect_connections', 10.0), ('inspect_connections', 10.0)], simplified_outcome=None), DiagnosticActionResult(action=
name: Test -> Control module (PCB traces & relay switching path),
description: Perform a detailed continuity and voltage test across all PCB traces and solder joints relating to the switched relay output path inside the control module. This will check for unexpected high-resistance junctions, poor solder joints, cracked traces, or partial opens that might create high voltage drops only under load, rather than under no-load continuity testing., outcome='All continuity measurements for the control relay and both output cables are nominal, indicating no detected high resistance or partial opens. Voltage testing shows that the relay is seeing nearly full supply voltage at its positive port, but the output cables are registering significantly lower voltages (0.3592 V and 0.0003 V), which is unexpected given the relay voltage. No polarity inversion is detected in the cable labeling based on your results.\nCurrent persistent circuit state [differences with the starting state]:\nNo circuit-level changes introduced by diagnostics.', precise_action_cost=120.0, cost_breakdown=[('test_continuity', 20.0), ('test_continuity', 20.0), ('test_continuity', 20.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0)], simplified_outcome=None), DiagnosticActionResult(action=
name: Test -> ambient light sensor (control module) and relay drive circuit,
description: Test for any unexpected current path or leakage (such as a short or partial short) between the sensor/indicator/relay drive circuit and the switched output in the control module, by measuring current and voltage with and without the load attached. Look for evidence of current leakage that could explain the large voltage drop under load., outcome='The measurements show negligible voltage and zero current across both the Internal Indicator Lamp and the Main Load (lamp), indicating no current flow through either. The control relay has full voltage across it but zero current, suggesting it is not activating or completing the circuit. No current leakage or unexpected current paths were detected in the tested branches.\nCurrent persistent circuit state [differences with the starting state]:\nNo circuit-level changes introduced by diagnostics.', precise_action_cost=160.0, cost_breakdown=[('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('measure_current', 20.0), ('measure_current', 20.0), ('measure_current', 20.0), ('measure_current', 20.0)], simplified_outcome=None), DiagnosticActionResult(action=
name: Test -> control relay coil drive voltage (control module),
description: Test the voltage across the relay coil in the control module while attempting to activate the relay. Verify if the relay coil is being properly energized, and if it actually switches when the control circuit triggers it. This will determine if the relay is mechanically or electrically switching as intended, or if the issue is with the actual relay actuation rather than its contacts or the output path., outcome='The relay coil is receiving approximately 12 V across its terminals, and the relay is visually confirmed to be in the closed (activated) state with no observable internal faults. The relay appears to be properly energized and switching as expected.\nCurrent persistent circuit state [differences with the starting state]:\nNo circuit-level changes introduced by diagnostics.', precise_action_cost=30.0, cost_breakdown=[('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('observe_component', 10.0)], simplified_outcome=None), DiagnosticActionResult(action=
name: Test -> Switched cable output under load (control module to load module),
description: With the lamp load disconnected, measure the voltage at the control module's switched output terminals, and then repeat the measurement with the lamp load reconnected. Compare the two measurements to determine if a significant voltage drop (from ~12V to ~0.36V) only occurs under load. This will help determine if the problem is related to a high resistance or current-limiting effect in the switching path that is only revealed under load., outcome="The voltage measured at 'Control Output Cable (+)' is 0.36 V both with and without the lamp load connected, and 'Control Output Cable (−)' is at 0.0003 V in both cases. There is no significant voltage drop under load.\nCurrent persistent circuit state [differences with the starting state]:\nNo circuit-level changes introduced by diagnostics.", precise_action_cost=80.0, cost_breakdown=[('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0)], simplified_outcome=None), DiagnosticActionResult(action=
name: Test -> Control module (complete internal wiring and components, including relay voltage at both input and output, and all PCB traces),
description: Perform a systematic voltage mapping throughout the control module, measuring at the relay input, relay output, indicator LED/anode/cathode, and the actual pins of the cable connectors themselves, during the on-off cycling (with the lamp load connected). This will determine exactly where the ~12V is being lost between the relay and the output connector, and if the relay is actually passing voltage on its output pin., outcome='The voltage at the control relay input and control input cable (+) is ~12V, indicating expected supply. However, the control output cable (+) only shows 0.36V, and the control output cable (−) is near 0V, indicating a significant voltage drop between the relay and the output connector. No polarity inversion is detected in the measured cables; the low output voltage suggests an issue with the relay passing voltage through to the output.\nCurrent persistent circuit state [differences with the starting state]:\nNo circuit-level changes introduced by diagnostics.', precise_action_cost=120.0, cost_breakdown=[('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0)], simplified_outcome=None), DiagnosticActionResult(action=
name: Observe -> Relay output to cable connector (physical inspection),
description: Visually inspect the physical connection and solder joints where the relay output connects to the cable connector inside the control module. Check for solder bridges, cold or cracked joints, or a disconnected output pin that might create an open circuit or prevent voltage from reaching the output, despite good PCB and relay measurements., outcome='The visual inspection showed no observable internal faults, solder bridges, cold or cracked joints, or disconnected pins at the relay or the cable connectors. Both Control Output Cable (+) and (−) are connected, with the (+) and (−) ports not visible but showing no faults. No POLARITY INVERSION detected based on the information provided.\nCurrent persistent circuit state [differences with the starting state]:\nNo circuit-level changes introduced by diagnostics.', precise_action_cost=30.0, cost_breakdown=[('observe_component', 10.0), ('observe_component', 10.0), ('observe_component', 10.0)], simplified_outcome=None), DiagnosticActionResult(action=
name: Test -> Control Output Cable (+) (physical cable itself, between control module and load module),
description: Perform a continuity and resistance test on the physical Control Output Cable (+) (not just its terminals/connectors), end-to-end, while flexing the cable slightly. This will verify if there is an internal break or high resistance inside the wire itself that continuity tests at the ends might miss., outcome='The continuity and resistance test of the Control Output Cable (+) is nominal, with measured resistance matching the nominal value (0.10 Ω). No internal breaks or high resistance were detected during the test.\nCurrent persistent circuit state [differences with the starting state]:\nNo circuit-level changes introduced by diagnostics.', precise_action_cost=20.0, cost_breakdown=[('test_continuity', 20.0)], simplified_outcome=None), DiagnosticActionResult(action=
name: Test -> Control Output Cable (−) (entire path: connections, terminals, cable),
description: Perform a continuity, resistance, and voltage drop test across the entire Control Output Cable (−) and its terminals/connectors while flexing the wire. Even though the (+) path checks out, an issue on the (−) path (high resistance, internal break, loose or corroded connection) could cause the observed low voltage in the output circuit and prevent current flow through the load., outcome='Continuity and resistance for the Control Output Cable (−) are nominal at 0.10 Ω. Voltage measured at the cable is also nominal (0.0003 V), with no issues detected in the (−) path during testing.\nCurrent persistent circuit state [differences with the starting state]:\nNo circuit-level changes introduced by diagnostics.', precise_action_cost=40.0, cost_breakdown=[('test_continuity', 20.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0)], simplified_outcome=None)] 
